<HEADLINE>
Bomb injures two paramilitary soldiers in southwestern Pakistan
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
QUETTA, Pakistan
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A bomb exploded near a railway track in Pakistan's southwestern Baluchistan
province on Friday, injuring two soldiers, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Local residents had found what they thought might be a bomb, and the device
exploded as the soldiers were examining it, said spokesman Lt. Col. Rizwan
Malik. The injured soldiers were in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened in Bakhtiarabad, a town about 250 kilometers (155 miles)
southeast of Baluchistan's capital of Quetta.
</P>
<P>
Baluchistan has seen a wave of small bombings and rocket attacks blamed on
tribesmen angered by government plans to build new military garrisons in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Also Friday, a bomb blast toppled a large electricity pylon under a high voltage
power line, disrupting electricity supply to about 5,000 homes in the area of
Mach, southeast of Quetta, said Jibraeel Khan, a spokesman for the state-run
utility.
</P>
<P>
Mirak Baluch, a purported spokesman for Baluchistan Liberation Army, a group
that claims to speak for the rights of Baluchistan, claimed responsibility for
the explosion targeting the power line.
</P>
